<section id="about" class="fade-in">
  <span class="sec-lbl" id="lAbout">About Karnataka</span>
  <h2 class="sec-title" id="aboutTitle">The <em>Sandalwood State</em></h2>
  <p class="sec-body" id="aboutBody">Karnataka — the land of sandalwood, silk and the Carnatic musical tradition — is one of the Indian subcontinent's most historically layered and geographically diverse states. From the Deccan Plateau in the north to the Western Ghats rainforests in the west, from the Coorg coffee estates to the arid Bellary iron-ore country, Karnataka spans extraordinary ecological and cultural range. Its history is measured in dynasties of staggering grandeur: the Hoysalas, whose 12th–13th century temples at Belur, Halebidu and Somnathpur contain the most intricate stone carving on earth; the Vijayanagara Empire, which from its capital at Hampi ruled the largest Hindu kingdom in history and whose ruins — UNESCO World Heritage Site — spread across 26 sq km of bouldered landscape on the Tungabhadra river; the Wadiyar dynasty of Mysore, whose kingdom produced the world's first electric street lights outside North America and whose Dasara procession is India's most spectacular royal pageant. Bengaluru — Silicon Valley of India and the country's fastest-growing city — hosts the world's largest startup ecosystem outside the US. Karnataka produces 80% of India's sandalwood, 70% of India's coffee and 30% of India's silk. The Western Ghats — Karnataka's forested spine — is a UNESCO World Heritage Site and one of only eight biological hotspots on earth, home to tigers, Asian elephants, lions, leopards and thousands of endemic plant and animal species. The Tungabhadra, Cauvery, Krishna and Sharavathi rivers descend from these hills through temple towns, wildlife reserves and hydro-power cascades. Karnataka's music — both Carnatic classical and the folk traditions of Yakshagana — represents some of India's most sophisticated performing arts. The state speaks Kannada — one of the oldest living languages, with a literary tradition of 1,500 years — alongside Tulu, Kodava, Konkani, Beary and dozens of tribal tongues. Karnataka is India thinking ancient thoughts in a modern city, brewing coffee in a rainforest, carving stone with divine patience, and celebrating with the roar of ten thousand elephants at Mysuru Dasara.</p>
