const placesData=[
{emoji:"🏛️",name:"Hampi — Vijayanagara Empire Ruins",location:"Vijayanagara District",desc:"UNESCO World Heritage Site — the ruins of one of the largest pre-colonial cities in the world, capital of the Vijayanagara Empire that ruled most of South India from 1336 to 1565 AD. Spread across 26 sq km of extraordinary boulder-strewn landscape on the Tungabhadra river. The Vittala Temple's stone chariot, the Virupaksha Temple still in active worship, the Royal Enclosure and the Lotus Mahal create a city that time has made more beautiful.",fee:["Rs.40 Indians","Rs.600 Foreigners"]},
{emoji:"🛕",name:"Hoysala Temples — Belur & Halebidu",location:"Hassan District",desc:"The most intricately carved temples on earth — built by the Hoysala dynasty in the 12th–13th centuries. The Chennakeshava Temple at Belur and the Hoysaleshwara Temple at Halebidu have exterior walls covered in hundreds of horizontal friezes of elephants, horses, scrolling foliage, mythological scenes and exquisitely detailed deity figures. UNESCO World Heritage Site. Sculptors worked for over 100 years on each temple.",fee:["Rs.25 Indians","Rs.300 Foreigners"]},
{emoji:"🏰",name:"Mysore Palace (Amba Vilas)",location:"Mysuru",desc:"One of the most visited buildings in India — the Indo-Saracenic palace of the Wadiyar dynasty, built 1912, illuminated by 100,000 light bulbs every Sunday evening and during Dasara. The Durbar Hall's painted ceiling and carved teak doors, the golden howdah (elephant throne), the marriage pavilion and the sheer grandeur of its 14 domes make this one of India's supreme royal monuments.",fee:["Rs.70 Indians","Rs.200 Foreigners"]},
{emoji:"🗿",name:"Badami Cave Temples & Pattadakal",location:"Bagalkot District",desc:"Badami contains four cave temples carved directly into the red sandstone cliffs — including an extraordinary 6th-century Vishnu temple with a cosmic vision of Vishnu reclining on Shesha (the cosmic serpent). Nearby Pattadakal is a UNESCO World Heritage Site — a cluster of 8th-century Chalukya temples representing a fusion of northern and southern architectural styles at the precise moment of their convergence.",fee:["Rs.25 Indians","Rs.300 Foreigners"]},
{emoji:"🐘",name:"Mysuru Dasara — Royal Elephant Procession",location:"Mysuru",desc:"India's most spectacular royal festival — 10 days culminating on Vijayadashami with a procession of 12 caparisoned elephants carrying the golden howdah through Mysuru's streets, followed by torchlight cavalry and a tableau of Karnataka's culture. Watched by one million people lining the route. Karnataka's own symbol of itself — simultaneously ancient ritual and living pageant.",fee:["Free (procession)"]},
{emoji:"🌊",name:"Jog Falls",location:"Shivamogga District",desc:"India's highest untiered waterfall — the Sharavathi river plunges 253 meters in four distinct cascades: Raja, Rani, Rover and Rocket. Most spectacular July–September when the monsoon fills the river. The sheer face of the Western Ghats cliff and the roar of the falls create an experience of raw natural power. The viewpoints above and below give completely different perspectives.",fee:["Free"]},
{emoji:"🐯",name:"Nagarhole & Bandipur Tiger Reserves",location:"Chamarajanagar-Kodagu",desc:"Two of India's finest tiger reserves sharing a border — together forming one of the most biodiverse wildlife corridors in Asia. Nagarhole's dense teak and rosewood forests shelter tigers, leopards, wild dogs, gaur and over 250 bird species. Bandipur is the most visited tiger reserve in South India. The evening safaris as light fades over the Deccan plateau are extraordinary.",fee:["Zone-wise charges"]},
{emoji:"🕉️",name:"Shravanabelagola — Gommateshwara Statue",location:"Hassan District",desc:"The world's largest monolithic statue — a 17.7-meter granite figure of the Jain saint Bahubali, carved in 981 AD on a bare hilltop. Every 12 years, the Mahamastakabhisheka festival anoints the statue with coconut milk, saffron, turmeric, gold coins and flowers from enormous scaffolding — one of Jainism's grandest events. The statue's serene face is visible from 25 km.",fee:["Free"]},
{emoji:"🌿",name:"Coorg — Scotland of India",location:"Kodagu District",desc:"A high-altitude plateau at 900–1,800 meters — blanketed in coffee and cardamom estates, misty peaks and rushing streams. The Kodava warrior community has its own language, cuisine and martial tradition. Abbey Falls, Brahmagiri Peak, Raja's Seat viewpoint and the Tibetan Golden Temple at Bylakuppe create a landscape of extraordinary beauty. The aroma of coffee blossom in March fills the entire district.",fee:["Free (estate visits charged)"]},
{emoji:"🏯",name:"Gol Gumbaz, Bijapur",location:"Vijayapura",desc:"The largest dome in India and one of the largest in the world — the mausoleum of Adil Shah II (1656) has a dome 44 meters in diameter. The Whispering Gallery just below the dome's rim transmits even the faintest sound across the entire circumference — a whisper is audible 36 meters away. The Islamic architecture of Bijapur rivals anything in the Mughal world for scale and ambition.",fee:["Rs.25 Indians","Rs.300 Foreigners"]}
