const artsData=[
{emoji:"🎭",name:"Yakshagana",location:"Coastal Karnataka and Malnad",desc:"Karnataka's supreme folk theatre — an all-night performance combining dance, music, elaborate costumes and improvised dialogue to narrate stories from the Mahabharata and Ramayana. The performers wear towering headdresses (kireethas), vivid face paint and costumes of extraordinary complexity. Yakshagana troupes tour coastal Karnataka and the Malnad region from October to May. It is simultaneously theatre, music, dance and ritual."},
{emoji:"🔔",name:"Bidriware",location:"Bidar",desc:"A 14th-century metal craft unique to Bidar — zinc alloy articles inlaid with pure silver in geometric floral patterns, then darkened with a special soil paste to create the signature black-and-silver contrast. Developed in the Bahmani Sultanate under Persian influence, Bidriware — GI-tagged — produces vases, hookah bases, jewelry boxes and decorative items of extraordinary refinement. Named for the soil of Bidar's fort that alone produces the right blackening."},
{emoji:"🧵",name:"Mysore Silk & Channapatna Toys",location:"Mysuru and Ramanagara",desc:"Mysore silk — woven on handlooms with pure gold zari (silk-wrapped gold thread) — is among India's most prestigious textiles. The Government Silk Weaving Factory established by Krishnaraja Wadiyar IV in 1912 still operates in Mysuru. Channapatna's lacquered wooden toys — GI-tagged — are made from ivory wood coated in natural lac in brilliant colors. Both are UNESCO-recognized craft traditions."},
{emoji:"🎵",name:"Carnatic Classical Music & Bharatanatyam",location:"Bengaluru, Mysuru, Dharwad",desc:"Karnataka is the heartland of South Indian classical music — the Carnatic tradition. Purandaradasa (1484–1564), born in Karnataka, systematized the entire Carnatic classical canon and is revered as the Pitamaha (grandfather) of Carnatic music. The Dharwad school of Hindustani music (overlapping Karnataka's northern border) and the Mysuru tradition of Bharatanatyam dance together make Karnataka one of India's supreme performing arts states."},
{emoji:"🖼️",name:"Mysore Painting & Tanjore Style",location:"Mysuru",desc:"Mysore painting — a classical South Indian style developed under Wadiyar patronage — is characterized by delicate detail, rich colors, gold leaf and a restrained elegance distinct from the bolder Tanjore style. Devotional images of Krishna, Rama, Saraswati and Lakshmi rendered in Mysore style have a luminous quality unique to the tradition. The Chitrakala Parishath in Bengaluru is the premier center for Karnataka's visual arts."},
{emoji:"🥁",name:"Dollu Kunitha & Veeragase",location:"Statewide — Folk Traditions",desc:"Dollu Kunitha — a vigorous drum dance where performers play enormous barrel drums while dancing in synchronized formations — is one of Karnataka's most energetic folk traditions. Veeragase — the fierce dance of Veerabhadra's devotees — features acrobatic leaping and extreme physical endurance. Both are performed at village festivals, Rajyotsava and Dasara processions, embodying Karnataka's folk vitality."}
