const cuisinesData=[
{emoji:"🍚",name:"Bisi Bele Bath",region:"Mysuru-Karnataka Heartland",desc:"Karnataka's most iconic comfort food — a one-pot preparation of rice, lentils, vegetables and a complex spice powder (bisi bele bath powder) cooked together with tamarind, jaggery and ghee until they become a unified whole. Served hot (bisi = hot, bele = lentil, bath = rice) with ghee poured on top, papad and pickle. A complete nutritious meal in a single vessel that embodies Karnataka's culinary philosophy."},
{emoji:"🫓",name:"Akki Roti & Ragi Mudde",region:"Statewide",desc:"Two Karnataka staples that define the state's food identity. Akki Roti — a thick, crispy rice flour flatbread mixed with onion, chili, curry leaves and coriander, cooked on a hot pan — is eaten across Karnataka for breakfast. Ragi Mudde — a heavy ball of finger millet (ragi) cooked until stiff — is the rural Karnataka staple, eaten with sambar or saaru. Both are nutrition-dense ancient grains prepared simply."},
{emoji:"☕",name:"Filter Coffee — South Indian Tradition",region:"Coorg, Chikkamagaluru, Bengaluru",desc:"Karnataka grows 70% of India's coffee in the mist-covered estates of Coorg and Chikkamagaluru. South Indian filter coffee — decoction brewed through a metal filter, mixed with hot milk and sugar, tumbled between tumbler and dabarah to create froth — is a ritual as much as a beverage. The Brahmin hotels (Darshinis) of Bengaluru and Mysuru have elevated the morning coffee to a cultural institution."},
{emoji:"🌿",name:"Udupi Cuisine",region:"Udupi-Coastal Karnataka",desc:"The purest vegetarian cuisine tradition in India — developed in and around the Krishna Temple at Udupi and spread across India by Udupi restaurants. Masala dosa (the crisp rice and lentil crepe with spiced potato filling — invented here), sambar, rasam, avial, coconut-based curries and banana flower preparations. Udupi cooking uses no onion or garlic — its complexity from spices, coconut and tamarind alone is extraordinary."},
{emoji:"🍛",name:"Kodava (Coorgi) Cuisine",region:"Kodagu",desc:"The distinctive cuisine of the Kodava warrior community — centered on pandi curry (pork with kachampuli, a tangy Coorg vinegar), kadambuttu (steamed rice dumplings), akki otti (rice flatbread) and payasam. Pandi curry — slow-cooked with black pepper, coriander, and the sour fermented kokum liquid — has a depth unique to Coorg. The Kodava community's love of pork and game reflects their warrior and hunter heritage."},
{emoji:"🍲",name:"North Karnataka Cuisine",region:"Dharwad, Belagavi, Bidar",desc:"North Karnataka's food is distinct from the south — jowar roti (thick sorghum flatbread) with enne gai (spiced eggplant in sesame oil), shengdana chutney (peanut chutney), zunka (dry chickpea flour preparation) and the famous Dharwad peda (a caramelized milk sweet — GI tagged). Influenced by Marathi and North Indian traditions, North Karnataka cuisine is bolder, heavier and entirely different from Mysuru or Udupi cooking."},
{emoji:"🥘",name:"Mangalorean Seafood",region:"Dakshina Kannada-Udupi Coast",desc:"Among India's finest coastal cuisines — Mangalorean fish curry (with coconut, red chilies and kudampuli), prawn ghee roast (prawns charred in ghee with Mangalorean masala until caramelized), Kane (ladyfish) fry in semolina, and Kori Rotti (chicken curry with crispy rice wafers). The specific Byadagi chili of Karnataka's coast — less hot but more red — gives Mangalorean food its distinctive deep-red color."},
{emoji:"🍬",name:"Mysore Pak & Karnataka Sweets",region:"Mysuru",desc:"Mysore Pak — created in the Mysore Palace kitchen, a dense golden cube of chickpea flour, ghee and sugar — is one of India's most beloved sweets. The palace version uses an extraordinary ratio of ghee that makes it crumble at the touch. Dharwad Peda (GI-tagged caramelized milk sweet), Belgaum Kunda (a milk sweet), and Karjikai (sweet fried pastry) round out Karnataka's remarkable sweet-making tradition."},
{emoji:"🫕",name:"Saaru & Huli",region:"Statewide",desc:"The two essential Karnataka gravies. Saaru (rasam) — a thin, peppery, tamarind-based soup poured over rice and drunk between courses — is both a digestive and a flavor palate cleanser. Huli (sambar) — thicker, with vegetables and a coconut-based spice blend — is the heartier accompaniment. The specific Karnataka saaru uses more pepper and less toor dal than Tamil Nadu rasam — subtle but completely different in character."},
{emoji:"🌽",name:"Benne Dose & Darshini Culture",region:"Davangere and Bengaluru",desc:"The Benne (butter) Dose of Davangere — a thick, crispy, generously buttered variant of the dosa served with a distinctive coconut chutney and potato palya — has become one of Karnataka's most beloved street foods. The Darshini culture of Bengaluru (standing-counter vegetarian restaurants serving idli, vada, dosa and coffee at extraordinary speed) is a unique urban food institution that feeds millions every morning."}
